{"id":"1602.03163","submitter":"Amit Chattopadhyay","authors":"Megan Davies and Amit K Chattopadhyay","title":"Stokes Waves Revisited: Exact Solutions in the Asymptotic Limit","comments":"4 pages, two columned; to appear in European Physical Journal Plus","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Stokes perturbative solution of the nonlinear (boundary value dependent)\nsurface gravity wave problem is known to provide results of reasonable accuracy\nto engineers in estimating the phase speed and amplitudes of such nonlinear\nwaves. The weakling in this structure though is the presence of aperiodic\nsecular variation in the solution that does not agree with the known periodic\npropagation of surface waves. This has historically necessitated increasingly\nhigher ordered (perturbative) approximations in the representation of the\nvelocity profile. The present article ameliorates this long standing\ntheoretical insufficiency by invoking a compact exact $n$-ordered solution in\nthe asymptotic infinite depth limit, primarily based on a representation\nstructured around the third ordered perturbative solution, that leads to a\nseamless extension to higher order (e.g. fifth order) forms existing in the\nliterature. The result from this study is expected to improve phenomenological\nengineering estimates, now that any desired higher ordered expansion may be\ncompacted within the same representation, but without any aperiodicity in the\nspectral pattern of the wave guides.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 9 Feb 2016 20:44:38 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-02-10"}
